column2: What are the primary learning goals for KBAI
column3: The primary learning goals are: First, this class teaches the concepts, methods, and prominent issues in knowledge-based artificial intelligence. Second, it teaches the specific skills and abilities needed to apply those concepts to the design of knowledge-based AI agents. Third, it teaches the relationship between knowledge-based artificial intelligence and the study of human cognition.
column4: The primary learning goals are: First, this class teaches the concepts, methods, and prominent issues in knowledge-based artificial intelligence. Second, it teaches the specific skills and abilities needed to apply those concepts to the design of knowledge-based AI agents. Third, it teaches the relationship between knowledge-based artificial intelligence and the study of human cognition.

Third, it teaches the relationship between knowledge-based artificial intelligence and the study of human cognition.

Third, it teaches the relationship between knowledge-based artificial intelligence and the study of human cognition.

column2: What is the structure of this course
column3: The structure of this course is driven by several pedagogical motivations: learning by example, learning by doing, project-based learning, personalization, collaborative learning, peer-to-peer learning, self-reflection and authenticity.
column4: The structure of this course is driven by several pedagogical motivations: learning by example, learning by doing, project-based learning, personalization, collaborative learning, peer-to-peer learning, self-reflection and authenticity.

column2: What will I learn in this class
column3: At the conclusion of this class: first you will have learned to be able to design and implement a knowledge-based artificial intelligence agent that can address a complex task using the methods discussed in the course. Second, you will be able to use this agent to reflect on the process of human cognition. Third, you will be able to use both these practices to address practical problems in multiple domains.
column4: At the conclusion of this class: first you will have learned to be able to design and implement a knowledge-based artificial intelligence agent that can address a complex task using the methods discussed in the course. Second, you will be able to use this agent to reflect on the process of human cognition. Third, you will be able to use both these practices to address practical problems in multiple domains.

column2: What is the Technical Report
column3: The Technical Report is a document that provides more detailed accounts of learning goals, strategies, and outcomes of this course.
column4: The Technical Report is a document that provides more detailed accounts of learning goals, strategies, and outcomes of this course.

column2: How is this class taught
column3: Each topic is taught through examples of the way in which humans and artificial intelligence agents approach certain problems, often building from human thought toward AI agents and subsequently referring back to human cognition.
column4: Each topic is taught through examples of the way in which humans and artificial intelligence agents approach certain problems, often building from human thought toward AI agents and subsequently referring back to human cognition.

column2: How does this course encourage Learning by Doing
column3: Students will participate in the reasoning within each particular lesson, and subsequently tie the topic back to a broader problem.
column4: Students will participate in the reasoning within each particular lesson, and subsequently tie the topic back to a broader problem.

column2: How does this course utilize Project Based Learning strategies
column3: This class has three projects, each of which build on the previous one, and the overall goals and motivations of KBAI are presented through these projects.
column4: This class has three projects, each of which build on the previous one, and the overall goals and motivations of KBAI are presented through these projects.

column2: Is Collaborative Learning allowed
column3: We encourage collaboration and the development of communities of practice surrounding the course material and projects. We are excited to see students borrow one another’s ideas and build on them, as well as spin off on their own study groups.
column4: We encourage collaboration and the development of communities of practice surrounding the course material and projects. We are excited to see students borrow one another’s ideas and build on them, as well as spin off on their own study groups.

column2: How does Peer-to-Peer Learning work
column3: During this class, students will give their peers feedback on their work for completed assignments. This lets students see additional approaches to the problems, provides extra feedback, and puts students in the position of a teacher, which has been shown to be a pedagogically useful role reversal.
column4: During this class, students will give their peers feedback on their work for completed assignments. This lets students see additional approaches to the problems, provides extra feedback, and puts students in the position of a teacher, which has been shown to be a pedagogically useful role reversal.

column2: How does this course encourage Self-Reflection
column3: At the conclusion of each lesson, each student is asked to reflect on what they learned in the class. Each design project requires the writing of a project reflection that explains and critiques, and reflects on the student’s work on the project.
column4: At the conclusion of each lesson, each student is asked to reflect on what they learned in the class. Each design project requires the writing of a project reflection that explains and critiques, and reflects on the student’s work on the project.

column2: How does this course ensure Authenticity
column3: The project that is explored in this class is an open research question in the AI and Cognitive Systems research communities. Two students from our lab have completed dissertations working on these questions in the past two years, and we have had papers published on these topics within the past several months.
column4: The project that is explored in this class is an open research question in the AI and Cognitive Systems research communities. column2: What components will determine final grades
column3: Your final grade will be determined by 3 written assignments worth 12%, 3 programming assignments worth 45%, 2 unproctored exams worth 35% and 24 peer feedback activities worth 8%.

column2: Do the grades assigned to me by peers affect my grade
column3: No. The primary purpose of supplying the graders with the results of the peer feedback process is to help the graders ensure every student gets useful feedback, as well as to ensure that the peer feedback received is accurate.
column4: No. The primary purpose of supplying the graders with the results of the peer feedback process is to help the graders ensure every student gets useful feedback, as well as to ensure that the peer feedback received is accurate.

column2: How will grades be released
column3: Grades will generally be released via both T-Square and Peer Feedback. Written feedback from the graders, however, will only be released via Peer Feedback. For Projects, sub-scores for your agent's performance on the problems and for your project reflection will be returned via the assignment submission page, and the overall project score will be posted to the grade book. Check marks for Peer Feedback participation will be provided throughout the semester via the assignment submission pages for those tasks, and a final Peer Feedback score (based both on completion and quality of participation) will be assigned at the end of the semester.
column4: Grades will generally be released via both T-Square and Peer Feedback. Written feedback from the graders, however, will only be released via Peer Feedback. For Projects, sub-scores for your agent's performance on the problems and for your project reflection will be returned via the assignment submission page, and the overall project score will be posted to the grade book. Check marks for Peer Feedback participation will be provided throughout the semester via the assignment submission pages for those tasks, and a final Peer Feedback score (based both on completion and quality of participation) will be assigned at the end of the semester.

column2: What advantages does peer-to-peer feedback provide me
column3: Peer-to-peer feedback provides a number of opportunities: it gives you the opportunity to see your classmates' work, it gets you more feedback on your work than you would otherwise receive, and it puts you in the position of critiquing and analyzing course material.

column2: How often will I be required to provide peer-to-peer feedback

column4: You will give peer-to-peer feedback to your classmates on all six assignments (including the three you do not personally complete) and on all three project reflections.

column2: How does peer-to-peer feedback impact our grade on the assignment

column2: Where will exemplary assignments be posted

column2: What is the point of posting exemplary assignments
column3: From previous semesters, we have found that posting exemplary assignments allow for greater peer-to-peer learning and fosters a community of learners.

column2: Is late work accepted

column4: Due to the size of the class and limited resources, late work will not be accepted.

column2: What should I do if I am having issues submitting my work
column3: If you are having issue submitting on T-square, immediately post a private note on Piazza with your submission.
column4: If you are having issue submitting on T-square, immediately post a private note on Piazza with your submission.

column2: What if I have an emergency and cannot submit my work on time
column3: If you have an emergency and cannot submit your work by the deadline, we ask that you go through the Dean of Student's office
column4: If you have an emergency and cannot submit your work by the deadline, we ask that you go through the Dean of Student's office

column2: What kind of issues can I bring up to the Dean of Student's office
column3: Justifiable excuses would involve any major unforeseen disruption to your classwork such as illness, injuries, death, and birth, all for either you or your family
column4: Justifiable excuses would involve any major unforeseen disruption to your classwork such as illness, injuries, death, and birth, all for either you or your family

column2: What kind of conflict am I liable for
column3: Conflicts such as weddings, business trips, and conference, you should complete your work in advance. That is why all of the assignments and project resources are provided to you at the start of the semester.
column4: Conflicts such as weddings, business trips, and conference, you should complete your work in advance. That is why all of the assignments and project resources are provided to you at the start of the semester.

column2: Is this course the same as the previous semesters
column3: No. every semester is a learning experience. Each subsequent semesters benefit from the lessons learned the previous semesters.
column4: No. every semester is a learning experience. Each subsequent semesters benefit from the lessons learned the previous semesters.

column2: Can I provide the teaching staff feedback on how I think that the course is going

column4: Absolutely! In fact, we encourage students to provide feedback on things that work, and things that could be done better.

column2: How can I provide feedback
column3: You may take advantage of the feedback box on Piazza, as well as the surveys we will send out over the course of the semester.
column4: You may take advantage of the feedback box on Piazza, as well as the surveys we will send out over the course of the semester.

column2: How many surveys will there be

column2: What if my conflict falls during the final

column2: When are assignments due
column3: All assignments are due at the end of the week, on Sunday at midnight UTC-12 (Anywhere On Earth time). This translates to an early-morning Monday deadline in the Americas, a midday Monday deadline in Europe, etc. If for example, Assignment 1 were due on January 22nd at midnight UTC-12, which translates to Monday, January 23rd at 7AM Eastern time, 4AM Pacific time. Precise due dates and times can be found in T-Square on each assignment page. Make sure to set T-Square to your local time zone to see due dates in your time
